webpackJsonp([71637120646596],{349:function(n,a){n.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Ulises Avila",profesion:" - Web Developer"}},markdownRemark:{html:'<h2 id="introduction"><a href="#introduction" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Introduction</h2>\n<p>Real life applications can reach thousands of lines of code. That is why developers are in the need of tools to categorize their code. </p>\n<p>The de facto standard to achieve it is called <em>module</em>. A module can export any type of object inside it, like functions and classes. In this article you are going to learn how to make a module in Python.</p>\n<div id="toc">\n<div class="center">Contents</div>\n<!-- TOC -->\n<ul>\n<li><a href="#introduction">Introduction</a></li>\n<li><a href="#creating-modules">Creating modules</a></li>\n<li><a href="#using-modules">Using modules</a></li>\n<li><a href="#conclusion">Conclusion</a></li>\n</ul>\n<!-- /TOC -->\n</div>\n<h2 id="creating-modules"><a href="#creating-modules" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Creating modules</h2>\n<p>Python has some interesting conventions around, one of them is that importing a file automatically gives you access to all names of it, that is the foundation of creating modules, every file is a module when called.</p>\n<p>To apply this we are creating a custom module, the code of has two functions, one for calculating the manhattan and other euclidean distance and one for a class called <code class="language-text">Point</code>, save it in a file called <code class="language-text">distances.py</code>:</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-python"><code class="language-python"><span class="token keyword">import</span> math\n\n<span class="token keyword">def</span> <span class="token function">euclidean</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span>point1<span class="token punctuation">,</span> point2<span class="token punctuation">)</span><span class="token punctuation">:</span>\n    x <span class="token operator">=</span> point2<span class="token punctuation">.</span>x <span class="token operator">-</span> point1<span class="token punctuation">.</span>x\n    x <span class="token operator">=</span> x <span class="token operator">*</span> x\n    y <span class="token operator">=</span> point2<span class="token punctuation">.</span>y <span class="token operator">-</span> point1<span class="token punctuation">.</span>y\n    y <span class="token operator">=</span> y <span class="token operator">*</span> y\n    <span class="token keyword">return</span> math<span class="token punctuation">.</span>sqrt<span class="token punctuation">(</span>x <span class="token operator">+</span>y<span class="token punctuation">)</span>\n\n<span class="token keyword">def</span> <span class="token function">manhattan</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span>point1<span class="token punctuation">,</span> point2<span class="token punctuation">)</span><span class="token punctuation">:</span>\n    x <span class="token operator">=</span> point2<span class="token punctuation">.</span>x <span class="token operator">-</span> point1<span class="token punctuation">.</span>x\n    x <span class="token operator">=</span> math<span class="token punctuation">.</span>fabs<span class="token punctuation">(</span>x<span class="token punctuation">)</span>\n    y <span class="token operator">=</span> point2<span class="token punctuation">.</span>y <span class="token operator">-</span> point1<span class="token punctuation">.</span>y\n    y <span class="token operator">=</span> math<span class="token punctuation">.</span>fabs<span class="token punctuation">(</span>y<span class="token punctuation">)</span>\n    <span class="token keyword">return</span> x <span class="token operator">+</span> y\n\n<span class="token keyword">class</span> <span class="token class-name">Point</span><span class="token punctuation">:</span>\n    <span class="token keyword">def</span> <span class="token function">__init__</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span>self<span class="token punctuation">,</span> x<span class="token punctuation">,</span> y<span class="token punctuation">)</span><span class="token punctuation">:</span>\n        self<span class="token punctuation">.</span>x <span class="token operator">=</span> x\n        self<span class="token punctuation">.</span>y <span class="token operator">=</span> y</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>With this we can proceed to use it normally as any other module.</p>\n<h2 id="using-modules"><a href="#using-modules" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Using modules</h2>\n<p>As we do not want to mix the logic code with the implementation code, we are creating a new file called <code class="language-text">main.py</code>, in this file copy the next code:</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-python"><code class="language-python"><span class="token keyword">import</span> distances\n\npoint1 <span class="token operator">=</span> distances<span class="token punctuation">.</span>Point<span class="token punctuation">(</span><span class="token number">7</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span> <span class="token number">9</span><span class="token punctuation">)</span>\npoint2 <span class="token operator">=</span> distances<span class="token punctuation">.</span>Point<span class="token punctuation">(</span><span class="token operator">-</span><span class="token number">4</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span> <span class="token number">8</span><span class="token punctuation">)</span>\n\nres1 <span class="token operator">=</span> distances<span class="token punctuation">.</span>euclidean<span class="token punctuation">(</span>point1<span class="token punctuation">,</span> point2<span class="token punctuation">)</span>\nres2 <span class="token operator">=</span> distances<span class="token punctuation">.</span>manhattan<span class="token punctuation">(</span>point1<span class="token punctuation">,</span> point2<span class="token punctuation">)</span>\n\n<span class="token keyword">print</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span><span class="token string">\'Euclidean distance: {}\'</span><span class="token punctuation">.</span><span class="token builtin">format</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span>res1<span class="token punctuation">)</span><span class="token punctuation">)</span>\n<span class="token keyword">print</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span><span class="token string">\'Manhattan distance: {}\'</span><span class="token punctuation">.</span><span class="token builtin">format</span><span class="token punctuation">(</span>res2<span class="token punctuation">)</span><span class="token punctuation">)</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>That program is importing our module, and using all of the code written on it without raising ay problem. Something important to note is that one has to use the dot notation to access any feature on it.</p>\n<p>After having executed the <code class="language-text">main.py</code> file the output will look like this:</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">Euclidean distance: 11.045361017187261\nManhattan distance: 12.0</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>And with this we end this part of the article, feel free to experiment with diverse inputs in the <code class="language-text">main.py</code> file to affect the output file, just remember that input is not being checked, so any wrong input data and the program will fail to execute.</p>\n<h2 id="conclusion"><a href="#conclusion" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>Create modules is really easy, with this one can focus on writing semantic code that solves a particular problem with the benefit of having a cleaner code. Modules also make sharing code easier, because of this it is important to learn how to do them, even though they are this easy.</p>\n<p>After this part one should look at how to create a library and share to the people through pypi.</p>',frontmatter:{date:"30 May, 2018",path:"/creating-modules/",title:"How to create modules in Python",category:"python",foreword:"Modules are a built in tool in the Python language that can lead to some benefits at development time."}}},pathContext:{id:"/home/ulises/Sites/ulises-site/src/pages/posts/python/creating-modules/creating-modules.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark"}}}});
